definition.value: An icosenoic acid having a cis- double bond at position 13.
A beta-D-glucoside that is egonol in which the hydroxy hydrogen has been replaced by a beta-D-glucosyl residue.
A dipeptide obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of N-acetyl-L-methionine with the amino group of L-phenylalanine.
A dipeptide obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of N-acetyl-L-methionine with the amino group of L-tyrosine.
An aryl sulfide that is thioanisole in which the hydrogen at the para position has been replaced by a methyl group.
A dipeptide obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of N-acetyl-L-methionine with the amino group of L-tryptophan.
A tertiary amine consisting of three dodecyl groups attached to a central nitrogen.
A glycerophosphoethanolamine that is phosphatidylethanolamine 32:0 in which the two amino hydrogens have been replaced by methyl groups
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine in which the two acyl groups contain a total of 31 carbons and no double bonds.
A glycerophosphoethanolamine that is phosphatidylethanolamine 32:0 in which one of the amino hydrogens has been replaced by a methyl group.
A dipeptide obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of N-acetyl-L-methionine with the amino group of L-alanine.
A phosphatidylglycerol in which the two acyl groups contain 36 carbon atoms and 1 double bond.
A dipeptide obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of N-acetyl-L-methionine with the amino group of L-serine.
A dipeptide obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of N-acetyl-L-methionine with the amino group of L-valine.
A phosphatidylethanolamine in which the two acyl groups contain 40 carbon atoms and 1 double bond.
A phosphatidylcholine in which the two acyl groups contain a total of 37 carbons and one double bond.
A dipeptide obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of N-acetyl-L-methionine with the amino group of L-threonine.
A zwitterion that is derived from 1D-3-amino-1-guanidino-1,3-dideoxy-scyllo-inositol 6-phosphate by deprotonation of the phosphate OH groups and protonation of the amino and guanidino groups.
Any peroxol formed by oxidation of the naturally occurring (4R) isomer of limonene.
(4R)-Limonene hydroperoxide where the hydroperoxy group is located at position 1 of the limonene skeleton; one of the two main allergenic hydroperoxides formed by autoxidation of (4R)-limonene.
A prostaglandin E obtained by formal oxidation of the 15-hydroxy group and hydrogenation of the 13,14-double bond of prostaglandin E1.

An organic cation obtained by protonation of the tertiary amino group of benzydamine. It is the major microspecies at pH 7.3 of benzydamine, which is a locally-acting nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drug with additional local anaesthetic and analgesic properties.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine in which the two acyl groups contain a total of 37 carbons and no double bonds.
A phosphatidylethanolamine in which the two acyl groups contain 40 carbon atoms and no double bonds.
A 3-sn-phosphatidyl-L-serine in which the two acyl groups contain a total of 40 carbons and 9 double bonds.
A phosphorus oxoanion resulting from the removal of one proton from the phosphonic acid group of tenofovir. The major microspecies at pH 7.3.
(4R)-Limonene hydroperoxide where the hydroperoxy group is located at position 2 of the limonene skeleton; one of the two main allergenic hydroperoxides formed by autoxidation of (4R)-limonene.
A digalactosylceramide consisting of an alpha-D-galactosyl-(1->4)-beta-D-galactosyl moiety attached at position 1 of N-(pentacosanoyl)sphingosine via a glycosidic linkage.
A digalactosylceramide consisting of an beta-D-galactosyl-(1->4)-beta-D-galactosyl moiety attached at position 1 of N-(pentacosanoyl)sphingosine via a glycosidic linkage.

A spirostanyl glycoside that is sarsasapogenin in which the hydroxy hydrogen at position 3 has been replaced by a beta-D-glucopyranosyl-(1->3)-[beta-D-xylopyranosyl-(1->4)-beta-D-glucopyranosyl-(1->4)]-beta-D-glucopyranosyl moiety. It is isolated from Asparagus officinalis.
A prostaglandin Falpha obtained by formal oxidation of the 15-hydroxy group and hydrogenation of the 13,14-double bond of prostaglandin F1alpha.
A member of the class of prostaglandins A that is prosta-5,10,13,17-tetraen-1-oic acid carrying oxo and hydroxy substituents at positions 9 and 15 respectively (the 5Z,13E,15S,17Z-stereoisomer).
A member of the class of prostaglandins A that is prosta-5,8(12),13,17-tetraen-1-oic acid carrying oxo and hydsroxy substituents at positions 9 and 15 respectively (the 5Z,13E,15S,17Z-stereoisomer).

A organophosphonate oxoanion obtained by removal of a proton from the phosphonate group of adefovir, a nucleoside reverse transcriptase inhibitor. It is the major microspecies at pH 7.3 (according to Marvin v 6.2.0.).
A leukotriene that is leukotriene E4 in which the terminal methyl grop has been oxidised to the corresponding aldehyde
A organophosphonate oxoanion obtained by removal of a proton from the phosphonate group of cidofovir. It is the major microspecies at pH 7.3 (according to Marvin v 6.2.0.).
A leukotriene that is leukotriene B4 in which the three methyl hydrogens at position 20 have been replaced by hydroxy groups.
A leukotriene that is leukotriene B4 in which two of the methyl hydrogens at position 20 have been replaced by hydroxy groups.
A leukotriene that is leukotriene E4 in which the terminal methyl grop has been oxidised to the corresponding carboxylic acid.
A leukotriene  that is (5S,7E,9E,14Z)-5-hydroxy-12-oxoicosa-7,9,14-trienoic acid to which a glutathionyl group is attached at position 6 via a sulfide linkage.
A leukotriene that is (5S,7E,9E,12R,14Z)-5,12-dihydroxyicosa-7,9,14-trienoic acid to which a glutathionyl group is attached at position 6 via a sulfide linkage.

A member of the class of leukotrienes that is leukotriene B4 in which the hydroxy group at position 12 has been oxidised to the corresponding ketone and the methyl group at position 20 replaced by a hydroxy group.
Any peroxol formed by oxidation of the naturally occurring terpene linalool.
Linalool hydroperoxide where the hydroperoxy group is located at position 6 of the linalool skeleton; one of the two main allergenic hydroperoxides formed by autoxidation of linalool.
Linalool hydroperoxide where the hydroperoxy group is located at position 7 of the linalool skeleton; one of the two main allergenic hydroperoxides formed by autoxidation of linalool.
An L-cysteine derivative obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of any long-chain fatty acid with the side-chain thiol group of L-cysteine.
A polyprenyl phospho oligosaccharide that consists of an alpha-D-Gal-(1->3)-alpha-D-GlcNAc moiety linked via a diphospho group to ditrans,octacis-undecaprenol.
Small guide RNAs employed for sequence-specific interference with invading nucleic acids by bacteria.
